    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Qu&ograve;d eo tempore, quo impletis Septuaginta annis, Juda[e]orum est resoluta captiuitas; Romani quoq[ue] &agrave; dominatu sunt regio Liberati. 
                        August. l. 18. c. 26. de Ciuit. Synchronismus perq[uam] memorabilis.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>That at the time when the seventy years of the Jewish captivity was completed, the Romans also were delivered from the domination of kings: 
                Augustine bk 18, c. 26 of the City of God. A very remarkable synchronism.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Tarquinij Apologia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Lucius Tarquinius Superbus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Apology of Tarquinius.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Brutus consul occisus.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Lucius Junius Brutus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Consul Brutus killed.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Indignus Regno Tarquinius, qui non pugnat acri&ugrave;s sa[e]uiusq[ue] pro Regno. 
                        Indomitam h&icirc;c Furiam esse oportuit; et Regem agere Diabolum: potiusq[ue] vitam perdere cum regno, qu&agrave;m opinionem Virtutis cum dignitate. 
                        Cogita, quo turbine h&icirc;c sa[e]uijssent duo perpetui Dictatores, Sylla, et Ca[e]sar; inuictissimi Armorum, Legumq[ue] Reges. 
                        Nuga[e] Tarquinij, qui tam cit&ograve; exacti, tam facil&egrave; subacti.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Lucius Tarquinius Superbus"/>
                    <person name="Sulla"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tarquinius is unfit to rule; he does not fight for royal authority very strongly and fiercely.
                There should be wild fury here, and the king should stir up the devil; he should rather lose his life together with his rule, 
                than his reputation of virtue together with his respectability. Think about the kind of whirlwind with which the two eternal dictators, 
                Sulla and Caesar, raged in this situation; they were absolutely invincible kings of arms and laws.
                Tarquinius' deeds were trifles, who was so quickly driven out, so easily conquered.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
